      Merchant cash advance
   =20
 =20

New York usury law makes it illegal to charge very high interest rates on l=
oans. If you charge more than 16% on a loan in New York, the borrower might=
 not have to pay you back; if you charge more than 25%, you might be commit=
ting a crime.
  [1]
 Some people want to charge higher rates on loans, and so they want to=C2=
=A0structure loans that don=E2=80=99t look like loans=C2=A0to avoid usury r=
ules.
The classic general way to do this is to structure the loan as a=C2=A0purch=
ase. If the borrower =E2=80=94=C2=A0sorry, let=E2=80=99s use a more neutral=
 word, maybe =E2=80=9Ccustomer=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0has an asset that wi=
ll pay $100 in cash in a year, you can=C2=A0buy=C2=A0that asset today for $=
80. You=E2=80=99ll get the $100 in a year, for a 25% return on your money; =
the customer gets $80 today instead of $100 in a year. That=E2=80=99s a lot=
 like the customer borrowing $80 today at 25% interest, but you have called=
 it a purchase and sale rather than a loan. Legally, this might or might no=
t work, depending on the details (if the asset turns out to be worthless, d=
oes the customer still have to pay you?).
Lots of quite normal high-finance lending works this way =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cstructuring a loan as a sale=E2=80=9D roughly characterizes things li=
ke the repo market,=C2=A0asset-backed securities=C2=A0or receivables factor=
ing=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but, also, lots of shady usurious low-finance lendi=
ng works this way.
  [2]
=C2=A0Or doesn=E2=80=99t work.=C2=A0We talked a few years ago about a usury=
 enforcement action against a company that bought legal settlements (from 9=
/11 first responders and football concussion victims); the company argued t=
hat it wasn=E2=80=99t making loans, but the regulators disagreed.
But this only gets you so far. Not all customers will have assets like that=
, financial assets that will provide a reasonably fixed amount of money in =
the future and that you can buy today at some negotiated=C2=A0discount rate=
. If you are lending money to small businesses, most of the businesses won=
=E2=80=99t have long-term contracts with AAA-rated counterparties that you =
can buy from them. Most of the businesses will have, like, a store, where c=
ustomers sometimes come in and buy stuff.
Naively, you can do a purchase of future sales: You look at a store=E2=80=
=99s books, you see that it usually brings in about $50,000 a month in reve=
nue, and you say =E2=80=9Cokay I=E2=80=99ll pay you $45,000 today for 10% o=
f your revenue for the next year.=E2=80=9D Then if the revenue stays the sa=
me, you get $60,000 ($50,000 per month times 12 months times 10%), for a 33=
% return on your investment. But that=E2=80=99s pretty risky, both for you =
(the revenue might go down, so you=E2=80=99ll get less) and for the custome=
r (the revenue might go up, so it=E2=80=99ll pay back much more).=C2=A0Actu=
ally=C2=A0buying a percentage of revenue feels more like a risky equity inv=
estment than a safe loan.
But you can make it more like a loan. One thing you could do is=C2=A0put a =
cap on the repayment: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll pay you $45,000 today for 10% o=
f your revenue for the next year, but capped at $60,000.=E2=80=9D That redu=
ces the risk for the customer: If the customer has a great year and doubles=
 its revenue, it still only has to pay you back $60,000. It doesn=E2=80=99t=
 help you, though: If the customer has a terrible year and revenue falls by=
 50%, then you get back only $30,000, less than you advanced to the custome=
r.
But add one more trick. Leave the cap the same,=C2=A0but increase the perce=
ntage of revenue that you are buying. Structure it so that the cap will alm=
ost certainly be the limiting factor on your repayment, and the percentage =
of revenue will almost certainly be irrelevant.
So the customer brings in $50,000 a month and you want to lend it $45,000 a=
nd get back $60,000, no more, no less. The trick is: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll =
pay you $45,000 today for=C2=A050%=C2=A0of your revenue for the next year, =
but capped at $60,000.=E2=80=9D Now, if the customer=E2=80=99s sales meet e=
xpectations, it will bring in $600,000 during the year, and 50% of that is =
$300,000,=C2=A0way=C2=A0more than you paid. But the customer doesn=E2=80=99=
t pay you the $300,000: It just pays you the $60,000 cap. If the customer=
=E2=80=99s sales fall by 50%, it will bring in $300,000; half of that is=C2=
=A0$150,000, but the customer will=C2=A0still pay you the=C2=A0$60,000 cap.=
 If the customer=E2=80=99s sales fall by 80%, it will bring in $120,000 and=
=C2=A0still=C2=A0owe you the $60,000.
  [3]
=C2=A0If the customer=E2=80=99s sales double, it will bring in $1.2 million=
 and still owe you $60,000. You get paid back the same $60,000 in all reaso=
nable upside, downside and flat cases. You put in $45,000 to get back $60,0=
00 in almost all cases, a 33% return with very debt-like characteristics.
Notice that the =E2=80=9C50% of revenue=E2=80=9D that you are buying here i=
s completely fictitious: You do not expect to get paid back 50% of the cust=
omer=E2=80=99s revenue. You expect to get paid back, exactly, the $60,000 c=
ap. It would be a surprise and a disaster=C2=A0if you got 50% of the custom=
er=E2=80=99s revenue: You and the customer both=C2=A0expect the revenue to =
be=C2=A0much=C2=A0more than $120,000, and you wouldn=E2=80=99t make the loa=
n (and the customer wouldn=E2=80=99t accept it) if you really thought that =
$60,000 would be 50% of revenue. The 50% of revenue is just a placeholder, =
a legal fig leaf, a way to=C2=A0call=C2=A0this a purchase and sale of reven=
ues rather than a loan.
  [4]

