Maybe the main way for things to go wrong in financial markets is the one t=
hat goes by the name =E2=80=9Cpicking up pennies in front of a steamroller.=
=E2=80=9D
  [6]
=C2=A0The shape of the problem is:
=09You think that tomorrow will look roughly the same as today.=09You make =
a bet of the form =E2=80=9Ctomorrow will be roughly the same as today.=E2=
=80=9D=09If tomorrow is roughly the same as today, you make a small amount =
of money.=09If tomorrow is very different from today, you lose a ton of mon=
ey.

This is not necessarily a mistake. Perhaps you have good reason to believe =
tomorrow will be the same as today, or perhaps you are being well compensat=
ed for the risk that it won=E2=80=99t be. Selling insurance is a classic fo=
rm of this trade, and insurance companies tend to be profitable. Still, pre=
tty much any time there=E2=80=99s a disaster in financial markets, you can =
describe the disaster by saying =E2=80=9Csome people got too complacent tha=
t the future would be just like the recent past, so they made big bets on t=
hat outcome, which they thought were low-risk, but=C2=A0those bets turned o=
ut to be riskier than they thought.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Sometimes, when this happens, the people making those bets were naive or st=
upid or reckless. Other times, they were making reasonable bets that offere=
d them fair expected returns for the risks they were knowingly taking, but =
things worked out poorly. They usually look bad in hindsight though.
The most schematic form of this is selling stock options: Buying stock opti=
ons is a bet on volatility, a bet that stock prices will move around a lot,=
 so=C2=A0selling=C2=A0stock options is a bet=C2=A0against=C2=A0volatility, =
a bet that everything will stay the same. Options-selling strategies look v=
ery good when volatility stays low: You make steady returns every day by se=
lling options that don=E2=80=99t pay off. And then when something changes, =
you can lose all your money. Again, this tends to look bad in hindsight. We=
 have talked about various disasters in this genre, investment firms that s=
ecretly or openly sold a bunch of volatility, showed their investors attrac=
tive stable returns for a bit, and then blew up horribly.
All of this is so well known that, now, when people are selling a lot of vo=
latility =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if volatility remains low and they haven=E2=80=
=99t blown up =E2=80=94=C2=A0there are a lot of raised eyebrows and worries=
 that those people are being naive. =E2=80=9COne of the Most Infamous Trade=
s on Wall Street Is Roaring Back,=E2=80=9D is the headline of this Bloomber=
g article by Lu Wang and Justina Lee:

Investors are sinking vast sums into strategies whose performance hinges on=
 enduring equity calm.
Known as short-volatility bets, they were a key factor in the stock plunge =
of early 2018 when they wiped out in epic fashion. Now they=E2=80=99re back=
 in a different guise =E2=80=94 and at a much, much bigger scale.
Their new form largely takes the shape of ETFs that sell options on stocks =
or indexes in order to juice returns. Assets in such products have almost q=
uadrupled in two years to a record $64 billion, data compiled by Global X E=
TFs show. Their 2018 short-vol counterparts =E2=80=94 a small group of fund=
s making direct bets on expected volatility =E2=80=94 had only about $2.1 b=
illion before they imploded.
Shorting volatility is an investing approach that can mint reliable profits=
, provided the market stays tranquil. But with the trade sucking up assets =
and major event risks like the US presidential election on the horizon, som=
e investors are starting to get nervous.

What is the opposite of this strategy? Traditionally, the answer is somethi=
ng like =E2=80=9Cbuying insurance.=E2=80=9D Some people sell options, betti=
ng that volatility will stay low, and the buyers of those options are peopl=
e who are more worried about volatility and who are looking to hedge.=C2=A0
But there is another possible answer, which is =E2=80=9Cgambling.=E2=80=9D =
Some people sell options, betting that volatility will stay low, and the bu=
yers of those options are gamblers hoping for a big lottery-like payout on =
a small investment.
  [7]
=C2=A0In some sense, casinos and actual lottery operators are in the busine=
ss of selling volatility, and those are good businesses.
I suppose how much you worry about short-vol strategies might depend on who=
 you think is on the other side. A story like =E2=80=9Csome exchange-traded=
 funds are selling options to investors who are hedging against a crash=E2=
=80=9D sounds alarming, for those ETFs:=C2=A0Shouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0they=C2=
=A0be worried about a crash too? A story like =E2=80=9Csome ETFs are sellin=
g options to retail day-traders who want some excitement=E2=80=9D sounds pr=
etty good, though: The gamblers are probably=C2=A0going=C2=A0to lose money,=
 and the ETF might as well take it from them. And gambling does seem to be =
up. Wang and Lee write:

=E2=80=9CThere basically is a natural increased demand for options because =
retail is speculating using the short-dated lottery-ticket type of options,=
=E2=80=9D said Vineer Bhansali, founder of volatility hedge fund LongTail A=
lpha LLC. =E2=80=9CSomebody has to sell those options.=E2=80=9D
That=E2=80=99s where many income ETFs come in. Rather than deliberately bet=
ting on market serenity like their short-vol predecessors, the strategies t=
ake advantage of the derivative demand, selling calls or puts to earn extra=
 cash on an underlying equity portfolio. It usually means capping a fund=E2=
=80=99s potential upside, but assuming stocks stay calm the contracts expir=
e worthless and the ETF walks away with a profit. ...
Derivatives specialists and volatility fund managers are so far brushing of=
f the risk of another =E2=80=9CVolmageddon,=E2=80=9D as the 2018 selloff ca=
me to be known. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Before the 2018 blowup, Bhansali at LongTail=
 correctly foresaw the threat from the growing short-vol trade. He reckons =
there=E2=80=99s little danger of a repeat because this boom is powered by c=
anny traders simply meeting retail-investor demand for options, rather than=
 making leveraged bets on volatility falling.

=E2=80=9CI am a canny trader simply meeting retail-investor demand to do so=
mething dumb=E2=80=9D is a great pitch for an investment product.

