<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">New York usury law makes it illegal to charge =
very high interest rates on loans. If you charge <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34642576.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnlzZW5hdGUu=
Z292L2xlZ2lzbGF0aW9uL2xhd3MvQk5LLzE0LUE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4965abb4" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">more than 16%</a> on a loan in New York, the borrower <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34642576.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
ubnlzZW5hdGUuZ292L2xlZ2lzbGF0aW9uL2xhd3MvQk5LLzE0LUE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cC4965abb4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">might not</a> have to pay you back; if you charge <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34642576.286368/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cubnlzZW5hdGUuZ292L2xlZ2lzbGF0aW9uL2xhd3MvUEVOLzE5MC40MA/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB22de5704" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">more than 25%</a>, you might be committing=
 a crime.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Some people want to charge higher rates on loans, and so they want to=
=C2=A0structure loans that don=E2=80=99t look like loans=C2=A0to avoid usur=
y rules.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The classic general way to do this is to struc=
ture the loan as a=C2=A0<em>purchase</em>. If the borrower =E2=80=94=C2=A0s=
orry, let=E2=80=99s use a more neutral word, maybe =E2=80=9Ccustomer=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0has an asset that will pay $100 in cash in a year, you c=
an=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>that asset today for $80. You=E2=80=99ll get the =
$100 in a year, for a 25% return on your money; the customer gets $80 today=
 instead of $100 in a year. That=E2=80=99s a lot like the customer borrowin=
g $80 today at 25% interest, but you have called it a purchase and sale rat=
her than a loan. Legally, this might or might not work, depending on the de=
tails (if the asset turns out to be worthless, does the customer still have=
 to pay you?).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lots of quite normal high-finance lending work=
s this way =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cstructuring a loan as a sale=E2=80=9D ro=
ughly characterizes things like <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/34642576.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2ZlZC5vcmcvbWFya2V0c=
y9kb21lc3RpYy1tYXJrZXQtb3BlcmF0aW9ucy9tb25ldGFyeS1wb2xpY3ktaW1wbGVtZW50YXRp=
b24vcmVwby1yZXZlcnNlLXJlcG8tYWdyZWVtZW50cw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc63fff3=
e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">the repo market</a>,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/34642576.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueWFsZWpyZWcuY29tL2J1bG=
xldGluL3JlZm9ybWluZy10aGUtdHJ1ZS1zYWxlLWRvY3RyaW5lLTIv/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB2adad305" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">asset-backed securities</a>=C2=A0or receivables <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34642576.286368/aHR0cH=
M6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvRmFjdG9yaW5nXyhmaW5hbmNlKSM6fjp0ZXh0PUZhY=
3RvcmluZyUyMGlzJTIwYSUyMGZpbmFuY2lhbCUyMHRyYW5zYWN0aW9uLHByZXNlbnQlMjBhbmQl=
MjBpbW1lZGlhdGUlMjBjYXNoJTIwbmVlZHMu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe1e48edc" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">factoring</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but, also, lots of shady usurious lo=
w-finance lending works this way.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Or doesn=E2=80=99t work.=C2=A0We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/34642576.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDItMDgvbG9hbnMtc2FsZXMtYW5kLWlwby1hZHZpc2Vyc=
z9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzExMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9=
bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMTEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB9a3d831c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked a few years ago</a> about a usur=
y enforcement action against a company that bought legal settlements (from =
9/11 first responders and football concussion victims); the company argued =
that it wasn=E2=80=99t making loans, but the regulators disagreed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this only gets you so far. Not all custome=
rs will have assets like that, financial assets that will provide a reasona=
bly fixed amount of money in the future and that you can buy today at some =
negotiated=C2=A0discount rate. If you are lending money to small businesses=
, most of the businesses won=E2=80=99t have long-term contracts with AAA-ra=
ted counterparties that you can buy from them. Most of the businesses will =
have, like, a store, where customers sometimes come in and buy stuff.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Naively, you can do a purchase of future sales=
: You look at a store=E2=80=99s books, you see that it usually brings in ab=
out $50,000 a month in revenue, and you say =E2=80=9Cokay I=E2=80=99ll pay =
you $45,000 today for 10% of your revenue for the next year.=E2=80=9D Then =
if the revenue stays the same, you get $60,000 ($50,000 per month times 12 =
months times 10%), for a 33% return on your investment. But that=E2=80=99s =
pretty risky, both for you (the revenue might go down, so you=E2=80=99ll ge=
t less) and for the customer (the revenue might go up, so it=E2=80=99ll pay=
 back much more).=C2=A0<em>Actually=C2=A0</em>buying a percentage of revenu=
e feels more like a risky equity investment than a safe loan.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you can make it more like a loan. One thin=
g you could do is=C2=A0put a cap on the repayment: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll pa=
y you $45,000 today for 10% of your revenue for the next year, but capped a=
t $60,000.=E2=80=9D That reduces the risk for the customer: If the customer=
 has a great year and doubles its revenue, it still only has to pay you bac=
k $60,000. It doesn=E2=80=99t help you, though: If the customer has a terri=
ble year and revenue falls by 50%, then you get back only $30,000, less tha=
n you advanced to the customer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But add one more trick. Leave the cap the same=
,=C2=A0but increase the percentage of revenue that you are buying. Structur=
e it so that the cap will almost certainly be the limiting factor on your r=
epayment, and the percentage of revenue will almost certainly be irrelevant=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the customer brings in $50,000 a month and =
you want to lend it $45,000 and get back $60,000, no more, no less. The tri=
ck is: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll pay you $45,000 today for=C2=A0<em>50%=C2=A0</=
em>of your revenue for the next year, but capped at $60,000.=E2=80=9D Now, =
if the customer=E2=80=99s sales meet expectations, it will bring in $600,00=
0 during the year, and 50% of that is $300,000,=C2=A0<em>way=C2=A0</em>more=
 than you paid. But the customer doesn=E2=80=99t pay you the $300,000: It j=
ust pays you the $60,000 cap. If the customer=E2=80=99s sales fall by 50%, =
it will bring in $300,000; half of that is=C2=A0$150,000, but the customer =
will=C2=A0still pay you the=C2=A0$60,000 cap. If the customer=E2=80=99s sal=
es fall by 80%, it will bring in $120,000 and=C2=A0<em>still=C2=A0</em>owe =
you the $60,000.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If the customer=E2=80=99s sales double, it will bring in $1.2 mil=
lion and still owe you $60,000. You get paid back the same $60,000 in all r=
easonable upside, downside and flat cases. You put in $45,000 to get back $=
60,000 in almost all cases, a 33% return with very debt-like characteristic=
s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice that the =E2=80=9C50% of revenue=E2=80=
=9D that you are buying here is completely fictitious: You do not expect to=
 get paid back 50% of the customer=E2=80=99s revenue. You expect to get pai=
d back, exactly, the $60,000 cap. It would be a surprise and a disaster=C2=
=A0if you got 50% of the customer=E2=80=99s revenue: You and the customer b=
oth=C2=A0expect the revenue to be=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>more than $120,00=
0, and you wouldn=E2=80=99t make the loan (and the customer wouldn=E2=80=99=
t accept it) if you really thought that $60,000 would be 50% of revenue. Th=
e 50% of revenue is just a placeholder, a legal fig leaf, a way to=C2=A0<em=
>call=C2=A0</em>this a purchase and sale of revenues rather than a loan.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does this work? Ehh, I think it has a certain =
shady elegance. But, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/34642576.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjQtMDMtMDUvY2FzaC1hZHZhbmNlLXBpb25lZXIteWVsbG93c3RvbmUtY2FwaXRhbC1zdWVkLWJ=
5LW5ldy15b3JrLWZvci0xLTQtYmlsbGlvbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzExMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG=
1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMTEmdXRtX=
2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB78fb4368" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">no, n=
ot really</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yellowstone Capital, a pioneer in a form of hi=
gh-risk lending called merchant cash advance, was sued by New York=E2=80=99=
s attorney general for $1.4 billion for allegedly making illegal loans to s=
mall businesses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For years, Yellowstone lent money at rates tha=
t exceeded usury limits =E2=80=93 sometimes more than 800% annualized, acco=
rding to the lawsuit filed in New York state court in Manhattan Tuesday. Li=
ke other cash-advance companies, Yellowstone claimed those rules didn=E2=80=
=99t apply because the transactions were =E2=80=9Cadvances=E2=80=9D on busi=
nesses=E2=80=99 future revenue rather than loans. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yellowstone advanced more than $500 million in=
 2017 alone. Originally based in New York=E2=80=99s financial district, the=
n Jersey City, New Jersey, its salesmen worked the phones to pitch cash adv=
ances to florists, pizzerias, truckers and other small businesses. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the center of the lawsuit is whether the tr=
ansactions Yellowstone called cash advances are in fact loans. The advances=
 generally required daily payments. The company has said in court that thos=
e payments were flexible and depended on how much revenue the business rece=
ived. But, according to the attorney general, Yellowstone actually collecte=
d fixed daily payments and used =E2=80=9Cfraudulent measures=E2=80=9D to en=
sure borrowers paid no matter what.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is from Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Zeke Faux and=
 Zach Mider, the great=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/34642576.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9ncmFwaGljcy8yM=
DE4LWNvbmZlc3Npb25zLW9mLWp1ZGdtZW50Lz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzExMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1=
dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMTEmdXR=
tX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe6993659" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">chr=
oniclers of shady doings</a> in the merchant cash advance (MCA)=C2=A0busine=
ss. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/346425=
76.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRme=
ElVL3JQQTkwRjdmTkJNNC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB778576a0" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the co=
mplaint</a>, which describes various alleged problems, but the core of it i=
s just what I laid out above: Yellowstone (and its successor, Delta Bridge)=
 would theoretically=C2=A0buy a=C2=A0<em>ridiculously high=C2=A0</em>percen=
tage of a merchant=E2=80=99s future revenues, but everyone understood that =
it wouldn=E2=80=99t actually get that percentage of revenue, it would just =
get a fixed daily repayment<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For nearly all of Yellowstone=E2=80=99s and De=
lta Bridge=E2=80=99s existence, the =E2=80=9CSpecified Percentage=E2=80=9D =
has been mostly an afterthought =E2=80=94 Funders described it as =E2=80=9C=
irrelevant,=E2=80=9D just =E2=80=9Ca number on the contract,=E2=80=9D and s=
omething that was included in the agreements for ambiguous =E2=80=9Clegal p=
urposes=E2=80=9D but was almost never discussed internally or negotiated wi=
th merchants. Although Yellowstone=E2=80=99s and Delta Bridge=E2=80=99s agr=
eements state that the Daily Amount is intended to approximate the Specifie=
d Percentage of the merchant=E2=80=99s daily revenue, the reality is the Fu=
nders negotiated and set the Daily Amount based on how quickly they wanted =
to be repaid and did not use the Specified Percentage at all. =E2=80=A6 Bot=
h companies routinely entered into multiple concurrent MCA agreements with =
individual merchants, with a combined Specified Percentage that could reach=
 as high as=E2=80=94or higher than=E2=80=94100%.=C2=A0As a result, the Spec=
ified Percentage could not, in fact, be the percentage of revenue that Yell=
owstone and Delta Bridge purchased from merchants. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rather than approximating the Daily Amount, Ye=
llowstone=E2=80=99s President and many Funders understood that the Specifie=
d Percentage reflected a =E2=80=9Cceiling,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and was therefore =
properly set at a value exceeding the percentage of the merchant=E2=80=99s =
revenue actually approximated by the Daily Amount.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point of the percentage of revenue was to =
be so high that the merchants would never be able to say =E2=80=9Cwell, you=
 bought a percentage of my revenue, and my revenue fell, so I should be abl=
e to lower my daily payments,=E2=80=9D because the contractual=C2=A0daily p=
ayments were much lower than the supposed percentage of revenue. For legal =
reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, to make these loans seem like purchases =E2=
=80=94 Yellowstone had a procedure called =E2=80=9Creconciliation=E2=80=9D =
that allowed merchants to lower their payments (or get refunds on previous =
payments) if revenue went down, but because of how the parameters were set =
it essentially never worked:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By March 2020, the most common Specified Perce=
ntage that Yellowstone used in its agreements with merchants was 49%. The r=
esult was that only the few merchants who experienced a drop in revenue so =
precipitous that Yellowstone=E2=80=99s total collections actually amounted =
to fully half of their revenue during the term of the MCA could potentially=
 receive a Reconciliation refund=E2=80=94and a very small refund at that. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By Reconciling merchants=E2=80=99 payments aga=
inst a made-up, inflated Specified Percentage number that bore no relation =
to the Daily Amount actually negotiated by the parties, Yellowstone, Delta =
Bridge, and their Funders made it virtually impossible for merchants to qua=
lify for any Reconciliation refund. As one merchant explained, =E2=80=9CI c=
annot imagine that [my business] would have taken advantage of this reconci=
liation process, since reconciling [my business=E2=80=99s] payments based o=
n this 15% =E2=80=98Specified Percentage=E2=80=99 likely would have caused =
its payment amount not to decrease but to increase.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CRespondents issued Recon=
ciliation refunds on just 2.4% of their more recent Delta Bridge MCA deals =
since August 2022, 0.37% of their earlier Delta Bridge deals, and 0.06% of =
their MCA deals at Yellowstone=E2=80=94including zero prior to 2020.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, if you are buying some percentage of a c=
ompany=E2=80=99s future revenue, you will want to carefully negotiate the c=
ompany=E2=80=99s revenue recognition policies so that you get exactly what =
you paid for. If you are just making a loan, this is irrelevant: =E2=80=9CW=
ith limited exceptions,=E2=80=9D says the complaint,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CYellowst=
one and Delta Bridge did not have any policy or guidance concerning what qu=
alifies as revenue under the terms of their MCA agreements, when evaluating=
 Reconciliation requests from merchants.=E2=80=9D Things that they allegedl=
y counted as =E2=80=9Crevenue=E2=80=9D included =E2=80=9Cloans from family =
members=E2=80=9D of merchants, as well as cash advances from=C2=A0<em>other=
=C2=A0</em>merchant cash advance companies.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because apparently lots of these merchants too=
k out multiple cash advance=C2=A0loans.=C2=A0This led to various forms of c=
omedy identified by the attorney general. For instance, one company took ou=
t three separate loans from Yellowstone on the same day, each with a differ=
ent daily repayment amount ($1,490, $4,470 and $7,450). But:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Each agreement represented that it=
s Daily Amount represented =E2=80=98a good-faith approximation=E2=80=99 of =
25% of Maslow Media Group=E2=80=99s daily revenue. In fact, the Daily Amoun=
ts were not an approximation of Maslow Media Group=E2=80=99s revenue, which=
 is clear because under no circumstances=C2=A0could 25% of a single company=
=E2=80=99s revenue, approximated as of the exact same date, equal three dif=
ferent amounts.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fair. Also of course if you purchase 25% of th=
e same company=E2=80=99s revenue three times, then you have bought 75% of i=
ts revenue, which seems high. (How high are its gross margins, if it can af=
ford to pay 75% of revenue to you?) But 75% is not an upper limit. What if =
you do =E2=80=A6=C2=A0nine cash advances?=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yellowstone even entered MCA transactions wher=
e it purported to purchase all of a merchant=E2=80=99s revenue, setting the=
 Specified Percentage at 100%=E2=80=94 and then filed those contracts in co=
urt actions against at least two of the merchants.=C2=A0In one case, Yellow=
stone purported to purchase 250% of the revenues of a merchant called PLS S=
cientific. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For another example, Delta Bridge purchased 22=
5% of a merchant=E2=80=99s revenue, where the merchant had nine concurrent =
Delta Bridge MCA contracts, each with a Specified Percentage of 25%.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right, if you=E2=80=99re buying 225% of a comp=
any=E2=80=99s revenue, that=E2=80=99s probably not=C2=A0<em>really </em>wha=
t=E2=80=99s going on.</p>
