er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">genre</a>, investment firms that secretly or =
openly sold a bunch of volatility, showed their investors attractive stable=
 returns for a bit, and then blew up horribly.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of this is so well known that, now, when p=
eople are selling a lot of volatility =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if volatility rem=
ains low and they haven=E2=80=99t blown up =E2=80=94=C2=A0there are a lot o=
f raised eyebrows and worries that those people are being naive. =E2=80=9CO=
ne of the Most Infamous Trades on Wall Street Is Roaring Back,=E2=80=9D is =
the headline of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34=
642576.286368/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtM=
DMtMTAvdGhlLXNob3J0LXZvbGF0aWxpdHktdHJhZGUtcm9hcnMtYmFjay1vbi13YWxsLXN0cmVl=
dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzExMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U=
9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMTEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBc522662d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this Bloomberg article by Lu Wang and =
Justina Lee</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors are sinking vast sums into strategie=
s whose performance hinges on enduring equity calm.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Known as short-volatility bets, they were a ke=
y factor in the stock plunge of early 2018 when they wiped out in epic fash=
ion. Now they=E2=80=99re back in a different guise =E2=80=94 and at a much,=
 much bigger scale.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Their new form largely takes the shape of ETFs=
 that sell options on stocks or indexes in order to juice returns. Assets i=
n such products have almost quadrupled in two years to a record $64 billion=
, data compiled by Global X ETFs show. Their 2018 short-vol counterparts =
=E2=80=94 a small group of funds making direct bets on expected volatility =
=E2=80=94 had only about $2.1 billion before they imploded.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shorting volatility is an investing approach t=
hat can mint reliable profits, provided the market stays tranquil. But with=
 the trade sucking up assets and major event risks like the US presidential=
 election on the horizon, some investors are starting to get nervous.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is the opposite of this strategy? Traditi=
onally, the answer is something like =E2=80=9Cbuying insurance.=E2=80=9D So=
me people sell options, betting that volatility will stay low, and the buye=
rs of those options are people who are more worried about volatility and wh=
o are looking to hedge.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is another possible answer, which is=
 =E2=80=9Cgambling.=E2=80=9D Some people sell options, betting that volatil=
ity will stay low, and the buyers of those options are gamblers hoping for =
a big lottery-like payout on a small investment.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0In some sense, casinos and actual lottery operators are in the bu=
siness of selling volatility, and those are good businesses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose how much you worry about short-vol s=
trategies might depend on who you think is on the other side. A story like =
=E2=80=9Csome exchange-traded funds are selling options to investors who ar=
e hedging against a crash=E2=80=9D sounds alarming, for those ETFs:=C2=A0Sh=
ouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>be worried about a crash too? A sto=
ry like =E2=80=9Csome ETFs are selling options to retail day-traders who wa=
nt some excitement=E2=80=9D sounds pretty good, though: The gamblers are pr=
obably=C2=A0going<em>=C2=A0</em>to lose money, and the ETF might as well ta=
ke it from them. And gambling does seem to be up. Wang and Lee write:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere basically is a natural increase=
d demand for options because retail is speculating using the short-dated lo=
ttery-ticket type of options,=E2=80=9D said Vineer Bhansali, founder of vol=
atility hedge fund LongTail Alpha LLC. =E2=80=9CSomebody has to sell those =
options.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s where many income ETFs come in.=
 Rather than deliberately betting on market serenity like their short-vol p=
redecessors, the strategies take advantage of the derivative demand, sellin=
g calls or puts to earn extra cash on an underlying equity portfolio. It us=
ually means capping a fund=E2=80=99s potential upside, but assuming stocks =
stay calm the contracts expire worthless and the ETF walks away with a prof=
it. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Derivatives specialists and volatility fund ma=
nagers are so far brushing off the risk of another =E2=80=9CVolmageddon,=E2=
=80=9D as the 2018 selloff came to be known. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Before the 2018=
 blowup, Bhansali at LongTail correctly foresaw the threat from the growing=
 short-vol trade. He reckons there=E2=80=99s little danger of a repeat beca=
use this boom is powered by canny traders simply meeting retail-investor de=
mand for options, rather than making leveraged bets on volatility falling.<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI am a canny trader simply meeting re=
tail-investor demand to do something dumb=E2=80=9D is a great pitch for an =
investment product.</p>
